              <decoDesc/>
              <additions>
                <list>
                  <item n="1" xml:id="addition1">
                     <p>The larger sections have been noted between the columns by a later hand.</p>
                  </item>
                   <item n="2" xml:id="addition2">
                      <p>Other lessons have been added by later hands on the margins.</p>
                   </item>
                   <item n="3" xml:id="addition3">
                      <p>Many Greek vowels (<foreign xml:lang="syr">ܰ, ܶ, ܺ, ܳ, , , , </foreign>)have been added, in the first half, by a later hand.</p>
                   </item>
                   <item n="4" xml:id="addition4">
                      <p>Another marginal division, by means of Greek letters, is carried through part of the volume. Of these latter sections there are 72 (<foreign xml:lang="grc">ΟΒ</foreign>) in <ref target="#b1">S. Matthew</ref>; but in <ref target="#b2">S. Mark</ref> the numeration seems to stop with <foreign xml:lang="grc">ΚΓ</foreign> (<locus from="53b" to="53b">fol. 53b</locus>), and in <ref target="#b3">S. Luke</ref> with <foreign xml:lang="grc">Θ</foreign> (<locus from="73b" to="73b">fol. 73b</locus>), whilst in <ref target="#b4">S. John</ref> it does not appear at all.</p>
                   </item>
                   <item n="5" xml:id="addition5">
                      <p>The same person, apparently, who added the Greek vowels, has inserted, chiefly in <ref target="#b1">the Gospel of S. Matthew</ref>, some various readings from <bibl>the Harklensian version<ptr target="http://syriaca.org/work/162"/></bibl> (<foreign xml:lang="syr">ܚܪܩܠܝܐ</foreign>, abbreviated <foreign xml:lang="syr">ܚܪܩ</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="syr">ܚܪ</foreign>), e.g.foll. <locus from="5a" to="5b">5 a and b</locus>, <locus from="7b" to="7b">7b</locus>, <locus from="12a" to="12a">12 a</locus>, <locus from="17a" to="17a">17 a</locus>, <locus from="19a" to="19b">19 a and b</locus>, <locus from="22b" to="23a">22b, 23 a</locus>, <locus from="24b" to="24b">24 b</locus>, etc.; more rarely from other sources (<foreign xml:lang="syr">ܐܚܪܢܐ</foreign> or <foreign xml:lang="syr">ܐܚܪ̈ܢܐ</foreign>), e.g. foll. <locus from="26b" to="26b">26b</locus>, <locus from="32b" to="32b">32b</locus>, <locus from="33b" to="33b">33b</locus>, <locus from="35b" to="35b">35b</locus>, etc. Occasional attempts have been made to represent Syriac words by Greek letters; e.g. fol. <locus from="18b" to="18b">18b</locus>, <quote xml:lang="syr">ܡܶܣܳܪ̈ܝܴܬܳܐ</quote>, <quote xml:lang="grc">ΜΑⲤΑ</quote>; fol. <locus from="30a" to="30a">30 a</locus>, <quote xml:lang="syr">ܢܰܛܥ̇ܝܟܘܢ</quote>, <quote xml:lang="grc">ΝΑΤΕ</quote>; fol. <locus from="31a" to="31a">31 a</locus>, <quote xml:lang="syr">ܪ̈ܘܚܐ</quote>, <quote xml:lang="grc">ΡΟΥΞΕ</quote>; fol. <locus from="66b" to="66b">66b</locus>, <quote xml:lang="syr">ܐܶܣܛܰܣܝܻܢ</quote>, <quote xml:lang="grc">ΑⲤΤΑⲤΗⲤ</quote>; fol. <locus from="132a" to="132a">132a</locus>, <quote xml:lang="syr">ܣܪܝ ܠܗ</quote>, <quote xml:lang="grc">ⲤΗΡΙ ΛΕ</quote>.</p><!-- Enter vocalizations -->
                   </item>
                </list>
              </additions>
